The "All-in-One" Tree Function
This version allows you to toggle hidden files and "directories only" using simple flags, while defaulting to a clean 2-level tree.

Bash
# Usage: lt [level] [-a] [-d] [path]
# Flags: -a (all/hidden), -d (dirs only)
lt() {
  local lvl=2
  local args=()
  local eza_flags=("--lhF" "--git" "--tree" "--color=always" "--icons")

  # Parse arguments
  while [[ $# -gt 0 ]]; do
    case "$1" in
      -a|--all)   eza_flags+=("--all") ;;
      -d|--dirs)  eza_flags+=("--only-dirs") ;;
      [0-9])      lvl="$1" ;;
      *)          args+=("$1") ;; # Catch paths or other eza flags
    esac
    shift
  done

  eza "${eza_flags[@]}" --level="$lvl" "${args[@]}"
}
Why this is better:
Unified Command: No more remembering lt vs ltf. Just use lt for files, and lt -d if you just want the skeleton.

Hidden Files: Adding -a (or --all) now works seamlessly within the tree.

Flexibility: You can still pass a level as a bare number (e.g., lt 3).

Icons: I added --icons. If your terminal supports Nerd Fonts, it makes that "quick tree layout" much more readable at a glance.

