Piping eza to grep is a classic move, but there's a catch: Grep kills the tree structure. If you pipe a tree into grep, you’ll just get a flat list of matching lines, losing the visual context of which folder those files belong to.

To do this "the right way" while keeping the tree intact, we have two main options: using eza's built-in globbing or using a regex-aware tree filter.

Option 1: The "Smart Tree" Search (Recommended)
We can update your lt function to handle a search term. This uses eza's --recurse and -I (ignore) logic to "sieve" the tree.

Add this case to your existing while loop in the function:

Bash
      -s|--search)
        shift
        local search_term="$1"
        # We use a glob pattern to only show matches
        eza_flags+=("--recurse" "--ignore-glob=^((?!${search_term}).)*$")
        ;;
Why this is better than grep: It keeps the lines and hierarchy leading up to the file, so you see exactly where the match lives.

Option 2: The "Interactive" Way (FZF)
If you do a lot of searching, piping to fzf (Fuzzy Finder) is significantly more powerful than grep. It allows you to fuzzy-search your tree in real-time.

Add this alias to your .bashrc:

Bash
